{"key":"processedPost-12665409","value":{"id":12665409,"first":12664057,"last":19990404,"when":1275401966,"utime":"06/01/10 05:19 PM","content":"<blockquote>Quote:<br /><strong>realfuzzhead said:</strong><br />ohh really? thats odd, ive read people here saying to use wbs as an icing layer because it is a good contam barrierm do you have any opinions on my questions?</blockquote><br />You have it backwards.&nbsp; NEVER leave exposed grains on the surface.&nbsp; They dry out and then when the mycelium dies back, molds take over the exposed grains.&nbsp; This causes contamination, not prevents it.&nbsp; I've also read of a 'frosting' layer, but it's by new growers who learn after the first time they try it to never do it again.<br />The solution to a too-wet substrate is to adjust to field capacity before you pasteurize.&nbsp; If you just pour hot water over it, then you get the substrate far too wet.&nbsp; When you squeeze it, you squeeze nutrients that were absorbed into the water out too.&nbsp; Next time, adjust to the correct moisture level, and then load into bags or jars and slowly heat until the center of the substrate is 140F to 160F and hold it there for an hour.<br />RR","title":"Re: solution to your substrate being too wet"}}